It is important to point out that a fully Bayesian hierarchical model would indeed have been a natural and preferable alternative to the two-step model adapted here. However, the answers from such a combined model were found to be highly sensitive to the prior distributions of the lot variability parameter. Thus the two-step approach previously described was used to analyze the data. The parameters (rate constant and lag phase 

                              Ct

                        ) and their standard deviations estimated in the first step were further analyzed in the second step to account for the unequal uncertainty in these estimates using a model with heterogeneous error variances. This is, in a sense, equivalent to transporting the posterior distribution of the parameters of interest (slopes and change-points) to the next step; the plots of these posteriors are normal like and can therefore be reasonably approximated by normal distributions. In this sense, the uncertainties in the first step of the two-step approach used are accounted for to a reasonable extent in the second step.
